recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2020-2024 911 vehicles.  The front windshield and rear window may not be properly secured and can detach.
recalls.Consequence: During air bag deployment, an unsecured windshield may not support the front air bags as intended, increasing the risk of injury in a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will inspect and replace the windshield and rear window as necessary, free of charge.  Owner notification letters were mailed on August 30, 2024.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is ARA3.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.nhtsa.gov.

recalls.Component: BACK OVER PREVENTION: SENSING SYSTEM: CAMERA
recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2019-2025 Cayenne, Cayenne E-Hybrid, 2020-2025 911, Taycan, 2024-2025 Panamera, and 2025 Panamera E-Hybrid vehicles. The rearview camera image may not display when the vehicle is placed in reverse. As such, these vehicles fail to comply with the requirements of Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard (FMVSS) number 111, "Rear Visibility."
recalls.Consequence: A rearview image that does not display properly reduces the driver's view behind the vehicle, increasing the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Dealers will update the driver assistance software, free of charge. Interim letters, notifying owners of the safety risk, are expected to be mailed February 16, 2026. Additional letters will be sent once the final remedy is available. Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243. Porsche's number for this recall is ASB2. Vehicle Identification Numbers (VINs) involved in this recall will be searchable on NHTSA.gov beginning January 19, 2026.

issues.title: PDK Transmission Harsh Shifting and Lurching
issues.description: PDK dual-clutch transmission exhibits harsh shifting, lurching during low-speed maneuvers, and jerky engagement from standstill. Issue appears most commonly in stop-and-go traffic and parking situations.
issues.fix_description: Software updates, clutch pack replacement, or complete transmission replacement in severe cases
issues.prevention: Regular PDK fluid changes, avoid aggressive driving in traffic

issues.title: Turbocharger Oil Leak at Wastegate Actuator
issues.description: Oil leaking from turbocharger wastegate actuator assembly, causing oil consumption and potential engine bay smoke. Common on early production vehicles.
issues.fix_description: Replace wastegate actuator seals or complete turbocharger assembly
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, avoid extended high-boost operation

issues.title: Infotainment System PCM 6.0 Freezing and Crashes
issues.description: PCM 6.0 infotainment system experiences random freezing, black screen crashes, and unresponsive touchscreen. Navigation and media functions affected.
issues.fix_description: Software updates, PCM unit replacement, or harness repair
issues.prevention: Regular software updates, avoid extreme temperatures

issues.title: Carbon Ceramic Brake Disc Cracking
issues.description: Premature cracking of PCCB (Porsche Ceramic Composite Brake) discs, particularly on track-driven vehicles. Cracks typically appear around mounting holes or rotor surface.
issues.fix_description: Complete PCCB disc replacement, inspection of brake pads and calipers
issues.prevention: Proper brake cooling between sessions, avoid overheating

issues.title: Front Axle Lift System Malfunction
issues.description: Front axle lift system fails to raise or lower properly, gets stuck in raised position, or shows error messages. Hydraulic pump and sensor failures reported.
issues.fix_description: Hydraulic pump replacement, sensor replacement, or system recalibration

issues.title: Rear Spoiler Motor Failure
issues.description: Active rear spoiler motor fails causing spoiler to remain in fixed position. Motor overheating and gear stripping commonly reported failures.
issues.fix_description: Spoiler motor assembly replacement, gear mechanism repair
issues.prevention: Regular operation at various speeds, keep mechanism clean

issues.title: Fuel Injector Failure
issues.description: Direct fuel injectors fail prematurely causing rough idle, misfires, and reduced performance. Carbon buildup and injector tip failure reported.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed injectors, carbon cleaning service, fuel system cleaning
issues.prevention: Use premium fuel, periodic injector cleaning service

issues.title: Sport Chrono Package Clock Malfunction
issues.description: Sport Chrono stopwatch and lap timer functions fail to operate correctly. Display shows incorrect times or fails to start/stop properly.
issues.fix_description: Software update, instrument cluster replacement, or wiring repair
issues.prevention: Regular software updates, avoid moisture exposure

issues.title: Air Suspension Compressor Failure
issues.description: Air suspension compressor fails causing vehicle to sag, uneven ride height, or inability to adjust suspension settings. Compressor overheating common.
issues.fix_description: Air suspension compressor replacement, air line inspection, valve block repair
issues.prevention: Regular system inspection, avoid prolonged maximum load

issues.title: Engine Mount Premature Wear
issues.description: Engine and transmission mounts wear prematurely causing excessive vibration, particularly at idle and under acceleration. Track use accelerates wear.
issues.fix_description: Replace worn engine and transmission mounts with updated versions
issues.prevention: Avoid excessive launch control use, regular inspection

issues.title: Tire Pressure Monitor System Sensor Failure
issues.description: TPMS sensors fail prematurely causing constant warning lights and inability to monitor tire pressures accurately. Battery life shorter than expected.
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty TPMS sensors, system reprogramming
issues.prevention: Regular battery checks, proper tire mounting procedures

editorial.tagline: Peak 911: Where precision meets nuclear acceleration
editorial.hero_blurb: The 992 Turbo S represents the absolute pinnacle of the 911 bloodline, delivering 640 hp through Porsche's masterful all-wheel-drive system. This is the thinking person's supercar—devastatingly quick yet sophisticated enough for daily use.
editorial.essence: The 992 Turbo S distills decades of 911 evolution into the most capable street 911 ever built. It's a supercar that retains the soul and usability that made the 911 legend, while delivering face-melting performance that rivals dedicated exotics.
editorial.heritage: Born from the original 911 Turbo of 1975, the Turbo S carries forward five decades of forced-induction excellence. This 992 generation builds on the widebody legacy while incorporating modern aerodynamics and the latest PDK transmission technology.
editorial.design_philosophy: Porsche's designers pursued timeless functionality over flash, creating subtle visual drama through purposeful aerodynamic elements. The wide-body stance communicates capability while maintaining the essential 911 silhouette that's evolved, never revolutionized.
editorial.motorsport_history: While the Turbo S focuses on street supremacy rather than track dominance, it inherits DNA from decades of 911 racing success, including Le Mans victories and rally championships that proved the rear-engine layout's ultimate potential.
editorial.engine_character: The 3.8L twin-turbo flat-six delivers power with surgical precision—minimal lag thanks to variable turbine geometry, then a relentless surge that builds to an intoxicating crescendo. It's explosively powerful yet remarkably linear and controllable.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 8-speed PDK shifts with telepathic speed and intelligence, reading your intentions before you fully form them. Manual mode delivers satisfying paddle response, while auto mode seamlessly adapts from comfort cruising to attack mode.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The all-wheel-drive system distributes power with supernatural intelligence, allowing the chassis to rotate naturally while providing unshakeable traction. Active suspension keeps everything perfectly composed whether carving canyons or crossing continents.
editorial.steering_feel: The electric power steering provides precise, confidence-inspiring feedback with just enough weight to feel substantial. While purists miss hydraulic assistance, the accuracy and consistency are undeniable in spirited driving.
editorial.brake_confidence: Massive PCCB ceramic brakes deliver phenomenal stopping power with excellent pedal feel and fade resistance. The system inspires complete confidence even when repeatedly hauling down from triple-digit speeds.
editorial.sound_signature: The flat-six produces a distinctive growl that's both sophisticated and menacing—turbocharged whooshes blend with the classic Porsche burble, especially dramatic with the sport exhaust during overrun pops and crackles.
editorial.ideal_owner: Accomplished drivers who want the ultimate daily-usable supercar—those who appreciate engineering excellence and need a car that excels equally in morning commutes and weekend canyon runs.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Pure track-day enthusiasts seeking razor-sharp focus, those wanting maximum manual engagement, or buyers prioritizing emotional theater over clinical perfection.
editorial.buyers_summary: The 992 Turbo S is the most complete sports car money can buy, offering supercar performance with remarkable livability. While expensive, it's the definitive expression of what makes the 911 special—versatility, capability, and timeless appeal.
pros: Devastating real-world performance with all-weather capability
Exceptional build quality and daily usability
Timeless design that ages gracefully
cons: Eye-watering purchase price and options costs
Some lack of emotional engagement compared to naturally aspirated engines
Electric steering lacks the ultimate feedback of hydraulic systems
best_for: High-speed grand touring with supercar performance
All-weather canyon carving and spirited driving

expertReviews.title: New Porsche 911 Turbo S review | World's most capable sports car | Autocar
pros: Exceptional turning and handling precision with active rear steer
No turbo lag due to electrically assisted turbos and hybrid system
Outstanding versatility - excellent on track, road, and daily use
Phenomenal braking performance with great pedal feel
Impressive traction with wider rear tires
Very comfortable ride quality in soft damper mode
High build quality and fit/finish
cons: 85kg heavier than predecessor at 1725kg
Slight understeer at steady throttle due to extra weight
Convertible has less chassis rigidity than coupe
May feel fidgety on poorly finished roads
Not quite as engaging as GT3 on track
expertReviews.verdict: The 992.2 Porsche 911 Turbo S is described as potentially the most complete sports car in the world, offering exceptional breadth of capability. With its new 3.6L hybrid flat-six, electrically assisted turbos, and advanced chassis systems, it delivers phenomenal performance on track while remaining comfortable and usable for daily driving. Despite being heavier than its predecessor, the engineering excellence masks the weight penalty, creating what the reviewer calls an 'obscenely good car' that excels at being both a track weapon and practical daily driver.

expertReviews.title: New most powerful ever Porsche 911 Turbo S driving REVIEW with t-hybrid Launch Control! (2026)
pros: T-Hybrid system provides 711 horsepower with more spontaneous throttle response
Massive 800 newton meters of torque available between 2,300-6,000 rpm
Only 85kg weight increase despite hybrid system maintaining lightweight philosophy
Advanced features like GPS-saved lift function and electro-hydraulic chassis control
High-quality interior materials and real button feedback
Carbon fiber roof and wipers for weight savings
cons: Very high price point
Sound is less engaging than naturally aspirated engines - described as 'thin'
Most seats only available in animal leather with limited leatherette options
Confusing window control layout with blind buttons
Extremely stiff suspension even in normal mode
expertReviews.verdict: The updated 992 Porsche 911 Turbo S T-Hybrid represents the most powerful 911 ever with 711hp and impressive torque delivery. The hybrid system adds minimal weight while providing more responsive acceleration. However, the sound character is less engaging than pure combustion engines, and the suspension remains very firm even in comfort modes. Despite the high price, it maintains the classic 911 DNA while adding modern hybrid efficiency.

expertReviews.title: The new Porsche 911 Turbo S is the most powerful 911 ever! (2026 facelift)
pros: 711 horsepower with hybrid system
2.5 seconds 0-100 km/h acceleration
Electric turbochargers with energy recuperation
14 seconds quicker Nürburgring lap time
Anti-roll technology with EHDPDCC
Only 85kg weight gain for hybrid system
All-wheel drive with rear-bias
Largest ceramic brakes ever in Porsche 2-door
cons: No animal-free interior options yet
Tires are the limiting factor on track
Not most comfortable seating position
Heavy material usage in interior
expertReviews.verdict: The 2026 Porsche 911 Turbo S represents a technological leap with its 711hp hybrid system featuring electric turbochargers and energy recuperation. It achieves hypercar-level acceleration (2.5s to 100km/h) while maintaining relatively low weight gain. The reviewer emphasizes this delivers electric vehicle performance without the typical weight penalty, making it ideal as both a daily driver and track weapon.

expertReviews.title: Porsche 911 Turbo S Cabriolet review (992.2)
pros: Ridiculously fast and responsive
Excellent ride comfort and refinement
Easy to drive despite the power
Luxurious interior with 18-way adjustable seats
Practical with four seats and storage space
Minimal scuttle shake for a convertible
Amazing brakes and traction
Convertible roof operates quickly and quietly
cons: Very expensive at $598,000 before options
Limited luggage space especially with roof down
Speed sign recognition system can be annoying
Back seats only suitable for small children
Still has manual bonnet latch unlike some competitors
expertReviews.verdict: The 911 Turbo S Cabriolet is an exceptional blend of luxury convertible and sports car performance. Despite the high $600,000 price tag, the reviewer was convinced of its value after driving it. The hybrid powertrain delivers 523kW and is incredibly responsive, while the car maintains surprising comfort and refinement. It's easy to drive in various conditions and feels manageable despite its power. The convertible body is impressively rigid with minimal shake.

expertReviews.title: The 992.2 Porsche 911 Turbo S is Crazy.
pros: Over 700 horsepower with hybrid twin-turbo system
Explosive acceleration - 0-60 in 2.4 seconds tested
Much more comfortable than GTS while maintaining dynamics
Electro-hydraulic suspension helps manage weight in corners
EV-like instantaneous throttle response
Significant performance upgrade over previous generations
cons: Lost analog tachometer and turn-key start
Noticeably heavier than previous 911s
Not a necessary upgrade for 992.1 owners
Weight affects track driving enjoyment
Fully digital gauge cluster less characterful
expertReviews.verdict: The 992.2 Turbo S delivers transformative hybrid performance with over 700hp and sub-2.5 second 0-60 times, plus improved comfort over the GTS. While heavier and missing some analog charm, it represents the best hybrid execution in a 911. Current 992.1 owners don't need to upgrade, but 991.2 and older owners will find this one of the most significant generational improvements ever.

expertReviews.title: Porsche 992 Turbo S Review – Expensive? Yes. Worth It ...
pros: Incredible launch performance with all-wheel drive system
640 horsepower 3.7L flat-6 twin turbo engine
World-class performance, suspension, engine, and transmission
Great combination of physical buttons and screen technology
18-way adjustable seats with heating and cooling
Practical front trunk storage
Active aerodynamics with adjustable spoiler
Excellent Burmester sound system
Daily drivable despite extreme performance
cons: Poor paddle shifters with no feedback or sound
Piano black trim attracts fingerprints
Matrix headlights cost $17,000 to replace
Stiff ride in Sport Plus mode
Stock exhaust is too quiet (needs aftermarket)
Very expensive at $300,000 for newer models
Some climate controls require screen interaction
expertReviews.verdict: The 992 Turbo S is an incredible performance machine with world-class capabilities in every area - engine, transmission, suspension, and handling. While extremely expensive at around $300k, it delivers unmatched all-wheel drive launch performance and daily usability. The reviewer suggests 991 generation models offer better value at $150-180k with more physical controls and no particulate filters. Only the Tesla Model S Plaid launches harder, but lacks the soul of the flat-6 engine.
